IN	1 7- to 8-ounce red bell pepper, seeded, cut into 1-inch pieces
IN	2 garlic cloves, halved, divided
IN	1/2 cup panko (Japanese breadcrumbs)
IN	3 tablespoons unsalted butter, room temperature, divided
IN	1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese, divided
IN	3/4 cup drained mild Peppadew peppers in brine, 1 tablespoon brine reserved
IN	1/4 teaspoon ground ancho chiles
IN	1 1/4 cups (packed) coarsely grated extra-sharp cheddar cheese
IN	1 cup (packed) coarsely grated whole-milk mozzarella
IN	8 ounces medium shell pasta or gemelli
IN	Ingredient info: Look for panko at supermarkets and at Asian markets. Ground ancho chiles are available in the spice section of supermarkets and at Latin markets.
PR	Bring 1/2 cup water, bell pepper, and 1 1/2 garlic cloves to boil in small saucepan. Cover; reduce heat to medium-low. Simmer until pepper is soft, about 15 minutes.
PR	Toast panko in skillet over medium-high heat until golden, stirring often, 5 to 6 minutes. Transfer to bowl; cool to lukewarm. Rub 1 tablespoon butter into crumbs to coat. Mix in 1/4 cup Parmesan.
PR	Transfer bell pepper mixture to processor. Add Peppadews and 1 tablespoon brine, 2 tablespoons butter, ground chiles, and 1/2 garlic clove; then add cheddar and 1/4 cup Parmesan. Blend until sauce is smooth; season to taste with salt and pepper.
PR	Preheat oven to 400Â°F. Butter 8-cup baking dish (or 6 individual dishes). Cook pasta in pot of boiling salted water until tender but still firm to bite. Drain; return to pot. Stir sauce and mozzarella into pasta. Season with salt and pepper. Spoon pasta into dish. Sprinkle with crumb topping.
PR	Bake pasta until topping is crisp and sauce is bubbling, about 25 minutes (15 for individual). Let stand 10 minutes.
